The difference between the color systems of light and paint is called "additive" or "subtractive" color.

Subtractive color is the color system they teach you in elementary school with red, blue, and yellow primary colors. It works by taking pigments that, when hit by a white light, absorb all of the wavelengths in the color spectrum except for a range that is attributed to a particular color. When you blend different pigments, it further restricts the range to form different colors, "subtracting" the wavelengths. Eventually, adding enough different pigments will result in either brown (all pigments mixed together) or black (all wavelengths absorbed).

Additive color is the opposite - instead of "subtracting" wavelengths, you are adding them together in the form of light sources that emit specific wavelengths. The primary colors are red, green, and blue, and when added together they make the secondary colors cyan (green and blue), magenta (red and blue) and yellow (red and green). If you keep blending colors, you eventually end up with white, which is all the wavelengths added together. (This is why "computer colors" are in RGB format, a.k.a. additive color, since your monitor uses light to display an image.)
